const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How much protein do protein gummies actually contain?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Most protein gummies deliver between 10 and 20 grams of protein per serving. The highest-protein options use whey protein isolate or hydrolyzed collagen to pack more protein into a smaller gummy format. Products below 10g per serving are better classified as protein-enhanced snacks rather than meaningful protein supplements. For reference, a standard whey protein shake delivers 20-30g per serving, so protein gummies typically provide 50-75% of a full shake serving.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Are protein gummies good for post-workout recovery?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Protein gummies can contribute to post-workout recovery when they provide at least 15-20g of protein per serving from a complete protein source like whey. The International Society of Sports Nutrition recommends 20-40g of protein within two hours after resistance training to maximize muscle protein synthesis. A protein gummy delivering 15-20g can be effective, particularly when combined with a protein-rich meal or additional protein source within the post-workout window.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the difference between whey protein gummies and collagen protein gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Whey protein is a complete protein containing all 9 essential amino acids, including high levels of leucine, the primary driver of muscle protein synthesis. Whey is the superior choice for muscle building and post-workout recovery. Collagen protein is an incomplete protein that lacks tryptophan and is low in branched-chain amino acids. Collagen supports skin, joint, and connective tissue health but is not optimal for muscle growth. If your primary goal is athletic performance and muscle recovery, choose whey. If you want skin and joint benefits, collagen is more appropriate.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can protein gummies replace protein shakes?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'For most people, protein gummies should complement rather than fully replace protein shakes. A typical protein shake delivers 20-30g of protein per serving, while most gummies max out at 15-20g. The gummy format also tends to include more sugar and fewer grams of protein per calorie than a whey isolate shake. However, for situations where convenience matters most — travel, office snacking, gym bags — protein gummies provide a portable alternative that is significantly better than no protein at all.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Do protein gummies have a lot of sugar?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Sugar content varies significantly across protein gummies. Some products contain 5-8g of added sugar per serving to achieve a candy-like taste, while others use sugar alcohols (erythritol, maltitol) or natural sweeteners (stevia, monk fruit) to minimize sugar content. Products with 3g or less of added sugar per serving represent the best options for individuals monitoring sugar intake. Always check the nutrition facts panel rather than relying on front-label claims like "low sugar" or "sugar-free," which may still contain sugar alcohols that affect some people digestively.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'When is the best time to eat protein gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The optimal timing depends on your goal. For post-workout recovery, consume protein gummies within 30-60 minutes after training to capitalize on the anabolic window when muscle protein synthesis rates are elevated. For meal replacement or snacking, protein gummies work well as a mid-morning or mid-afternoon protein source to maintain stable blood sugar and satiety between meals. For general protein intake goals, timing is less important than total daily protein consumption — aim for 1.6-2.2g per kg of body weight spread across 3-5 meals and snacks.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Are protein gummies good for weight loss?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Protein gummies can support weight loss by increasing protein intake, which has the highest thermic effect of any macronutrient (20-30% of protein calories are burned during digestion) and promotes satiety. Research consistently shows that higher-protein diets preserve lean muscle mass during caloric restriction, preventing the metabolic slowdown that undermines many diets. However, protein gummies are only beneficial for weight loss when they replace less nutritious snacks, not when added on top of existing caloric intake. Monitor total calories, not just protein content.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Are plant-based protein gummies as effective as whey?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Plant-based protein gummies can be equally effective for total daily protein goals when they use a blend of complementary plant proteins (pea + rice, for example) that together provide all essential amino acids. However, plant proteins have lower leucine content per gram compared to whey, meaning you may need a slightly higher dose (25-30g vs 20g) to achieve the same muscle protein synthesis stimulation. For casual fitness and general health, the difference is negligible. For competitive athletes optimizing every variable, whey remains the superior protein source per gram.' },
    },
  ],
};
