    </div>

    <p>The critical question is whether protein gummies deliver enough protein to matter. A standard whey shake provides 20-30g per serving. Most protein gummies deliver 10-20g. That is a meaningful amount — roughly the protein content of 2-3 eggs — but only if the product uses a quality protein source with a complete amino acid profile.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Whey Protein Isolate</strong>
        <p>Complete protein with all 9 essential amino acids. Highest leucine content per gram (the primary trigger for muscle protein synthesis). Fast-absorbing. The gold standard for athletic recovery.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Hydrolyzed Collagen</strong>
        <p>Incomplete protein (lacks tryptophan, low BCAAs). Supports skin elasticity, joint health, and connective tissue. Not optimal for muscle building but excellent for recovery of tendons, ligaments, and skin.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Plant-Based Blends</strong>
        <p>Pea + rice combinations provide a complete amino acid profile. Lower leucine per gram than whey requires higher doses for equal MPS stimulation. Suitable for vegan athletes and dairy-sensitive individuals.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Casein</strong>
        <p>Slow-digesting complete protein. Provides sustained amino acid release over 4-7 hours. Ideal for nighttime protein supplementation but rare in gummy form due to formulation challenges.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2022 systematic review in the <em>Journal of the International Society of Sports Nutrition</em> concluded that <strong>total daily protein intake of 1.6-2.2g per kg of body weight</strong> is the primary determinant of muscle protein synthesis, lean mass gains, and recovery — regardless of whether the protein comes from shakes, bars, gummies, or whole food. Timing matters less than total intake.</p>
      <cite>JISSN, 2022 — Systematic Review of 49 Studies</cite>
    </div>

