    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Protein Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much protein do protein gummies actually contain?</summary>
      <p>Most protein gummies deliver between 10 and 20 grams of protein per serving. The highest-protein options use whey protein isolate or hydrolyzed collagen to pack more protein into a smaller format. Products below 10g per serving are better classified as protein-enhanced snacks rather than meaningful protein supplements. For reference, a standard whey protein shake delivers 20-30g per serving, so protein gummies typically provide 50-75% of a full shake.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are protein gummies good for post-workout recovery?</summary>
      <p>Protein gummies can contribute to post-workout recovery when they provide at least 15-20g of protein per serving from a complete protein source like whey. The International Society of Sports Nutrition recommends 20-40g of protein within two hours after resistance training to maximize muscle protein synthesis. A protein gummy delivering 15-20g can be effective, particularly when combined with a protein-rich meal within the post-workout window.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between whey protein gummies and collagen protein gummies?</summary>
      <p>Whey protein is a complete protein containing all 9 essential amino acids, with high leucine content for muscle building. Collagen protein is incomplete (lacks tryptophan) and low in branched-chain amino acids. Collagen supports skin, joint, and connective tissue health but is not optimal for muscle growth. Choose whey for athletic performance and muscle recovery. Choose collagen for skin and joint benefits.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can protein gummies replace protein shakes?</summary>
      <p>For most people, protein gummies should complement rather than fully replace protein shakes. Shakes deliver 20-30g per serving, while most gummies max out at 15-20g. The gummy format also tends to include more sugar and fewer grams of protein per calorie. However, for travel, office snacking, and gym bags, protein gummies provide a portable alternative that is significantly better than no protein at all.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do protein gummies have a lot of sugar?</summary>
      <p>Sugar content varies significantly. Some products contain 5-8g of added sugar per serving, while others use allulose, stevia, or monk fruit to minimize sugar to 1-2g. Products with 3g or less of added sugar represent the best options for macro-conscious consumers. Check the nutrition facts panel rather than front-label claims, as "sugar-free" products may still contain sugar alcohols that affect digestion.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>When is the best time to eat protein gummies?</summary>
      <p>For post-workout recovery, consume within 30-60 minutes after training. For snacking, they work well as a mid-morning or mid-afternoon protein source to maintain satiety between meals. For general protein goals, timing is less important than total daily consumption — aim for 1.6-2.2g per kg of body weight spread across multiple meals and snacks throughout the day.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are protein gummies good for weight loss?</summary>
      <p>Protein gummies can support weight loss by increasing protein intake, which has the highest thermic effect of any macronutrient (20-30% of calories burned during digestion) and promotes satiety. Higher-protein diets preserve lean muscle mass during caloric restriction. However, protein gummies only aid weight loss when they replace less nutritious snacks, not when added to existing caloric intake. Monitor total calories, not just protein content.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are plant-based protein gummies as effective as whey?</summary>
      <p>Plant-based blends (pea + rice) can be equally effective for total daily protein goals when they provide all essential amino acids. However, plant proteins have lower leucine per gram than whey, meaning you may need 25-30g (vs 20g for whey) to achieve equivalent muscle protein synthesis stimulation. For casual fitness, the difference is negligible. For competitive athletes, whey remains superior per gram.</p>
    </details>

